{"id":14881910,"mediaExerciseId":"a576579b-e9df-4166-8f3d-ec80a2d46981","exerciseName":"2","chapterName":"25","chapterTitle":"Option Valuation","groupId":612507,"groupTitle":"Critical Thinking Questions","isPremium":true,"sectionName":null,"sectionTitle":null,"pageNumber":855,"solutions":[{"id":6522004,"modifiedOn":"2021-01-01T00:00:00.000000","steps":[{"columns":[{"text":"In this exercise, we are going to determine the effect of the volatility of the underlying stock return on an option's value. ","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":1},{"columns":[{"text":"To start with, let us define **volatility.**\n\nStock prices changes over time, as well as the values of option. Market fluctuations are from the economic factors which affect the financial condition of the market as well.\n\nAnalyzing the stock prices and market over time helps to reasonably visualize the option's value.","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":2},{"columns":[{"text":"The volatility is measured by standard deviation. As the standard deviation increases, the price of the option increases as well. \n\nThe volatility and risk are directly related. Once volatility increases, the increased price of the option is to cover the increased risk, and the higher chance of the holder exercising his rights on an in-the-money option. ","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":3}],"rating":0,"solutionUuid":"9af3c755-dd11-4174-8a58-0b2dc42d7755","editorVersion":2,"answeredOn":null,"ratingCount":null,"solutionOrder":null,"totalSteps":3}],"textbook":{"authors":"Bradford D. Jordan, Randolph W. Westerfield, Stephen A. Ross","imageUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/textbook_covers/tmpm0p82b7h","imageThumbnailUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/cache/d1/d3/d1d34d106dd29dd2e